<p><span class="date">October 2025</span>:
<span class="description">Litao Yan presented his <a href="/assets/pdf/trailblazer.pdf">paper on Trailblazer</a> at UIST '25. The paper describes the design and evaluation of a tool for answering developer questions with agent-discovered program traces.</span></p>

<p><span class="date">July 2025</span>:
<span class="description">Congratulations Harry Goldstein, Penn HCI alum, on receiving one of SIGPLAN's two <a href="https://www.sigplan.org/Awards/Dissertation/">oustanding dissertation awards</a>. Congratulations as well on beginning your assistant professor position at UBuffalo.</span></p>

<p><span class="date">March 2025</span>:
<span class="description">Two projects from our group will appear at CHI! The first is Jeffrey Tao's <i>Freeform</i> editor for embellishing math notation with explanations, accepted as a <a href="/assets/pdf/freeform.pdf">full paper</a>. The second is Hita Kambhamettu's study of the effect of source-summary links on the reading of AI-generated text, which will appear as <a href="/assets/pdf/traceable-text.pdf">late-breaking work</a>.</span></p>

<p><span class="date">February 2025</span>:
<span class="description">Jessica Shi's <i>QED in Context</i> will appear in OOPSLA '25. The paper highlights strategies and obstacles proof assistant users face with their tools. Read the pre-print <a href="/assets/pdf/qed-in-context.pdf">here</a>.</span></p>

<p><span class="date">September 2024</span>:
<span class="description">This semester, I am teaching a new research seminar on <i>Interactive Reading</i>. Our goal is to develop technology that deepens, accelerates, and enlivens reading. Check out the <a href="https://youtu.be/R5nAhe7HTqc">course teaser</a> and <a href="https://docs.google.com/document/d/137dy6c1fimszDBp74LH3e_aKo1H8VqsN6PP1cy2ZQX4/edit?usp=sharing">syllabus</a>.</span></p>

<p><span class="date">August 2024</span>:
<span class="description">Harry Goldstein has had a paper accepted to UIST '24 on <i>Tyche</i>, a in-editor UI that helps programmers understand the comprehensiveness of their property-based tests. Read the paper <a href="/assets/pdf/tyche.pdf">here</a>.</span></p>

